In Dart Code we have a shortcut to show a type hierarchy using a picklist. When the user selects an item, we call openTextDocument then showTextDocument like this:

``` ts
vs.window.showQuickPick(tree.map(item => itemToPick(item, items)), options).then(result => {
    if (result) {
        let location: as.Location = result['location'];
        vs.workspace.openTextDocument(location.file).then(document => {
            vs.window.showTextDocument(document).then(editor => {
                // stuff
            });
        });
    }
});
```

I'm testing with a single file, where all code is in the same file (so `openTextDocument` and `showTextDocument` are both effectively doing nothing at all; the file is both open and visible). However, between calling showTextDocument and the chained method being called there appears to be quite a delay:

``` ts
console.log('Calling openTextDocument: ' + new Date().getTime());
vs.workspace.openTextDocument(location.file).then(document => {
    console.log('Calling showTextDocument: ' + new Date().getTime());
    vs.window.showTextDocument(document).then(editor => {
        console.log('showTextDocument done: ' + new Date().getTime());
```

outputs:

``` text
Calling openTextDocument: 1476459604276
Calling showTextDocument: 1476459604277
showTextDocument done: 1476459605282
```

There is **1005ms** between the last two timestamps. This results in a noticeable delay to the user in selecting the range (which we do inside that chained function).

I can't see any obvious reason why this would stall for so long (especially given it's not doing anything; the file is open (the only open file) and visible).

The file file with our code is [here](https://github.com/Dart-Code/Dart-Code/blob/18196fbc8586ec245acb4c0afbaa987efa37e513/src/commands/type_hierarchy.ts).
